The Trojan Horse of Europe
BERKELEY – Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
Emergency funds will have to be provided.
Conditions will have to be attached.
The Greek government will make the usual promises.
Cela devrait permettre au gouvernement grec de servir sa dette.
The markets will calm down.
Long-term consequences will not be prohibitive, but there will be problems ahead.
Some will say that the fatal mistake was allowing Greece to adopt the euro first.
It was already evident, however, that the country was not ready.
Its fiscal policy was already out of control when it joined the monetary union in 2001, and its unions were already pressuring for Greek wages to align with those in Europe, despite lagging productivity.
But this response is too simplistic, as such signs of dysfunction are not limited to Greece.
Spain, with a 20% unemployment rate and abyssal budget deficits, sees Greece as a mirror of its own future.
And if not, the markets will take care of it.
Portugal and Italy are doing slightly better.
Countries, just like Greece, must face significant budget cuts.
Like Greece, they cannot devalue their currency to encourage exports.
Like Greece, they must face a deep recession.
Like Greece, they will be tempted to seek aid.
All of this raises one question: was the real mistake not creating the euro?
Dans la mesure où j’étais l’un des rares américains à encourager l’idée d’une monnaie européenne, vous seriez en droit de me demander : êtes-vous en train de reconsidérer votre position initiale ?
Ma réponse est non, le fait de créer l’euro n’a pas été une erreur, mais cela pourrait bien le devenir.
La crise grecque montre que l’Europe n’est qu’à mi-chemin sur la voie d’une union monétaire viable.
Si elle ne fait rien, la prochaine crise pourrait bien faire passer celle-ci comme une promenade au parc.
Si elle veut achever son union monétaire, l’Europe devra créer son propre mécanisme de financement d’urgence.
Aujourd’hui, les membres de l’Union ne peuvent apporter leur aide à la Grèce qu’en outrepassant la réglementation qui les empêche d’accorder un prêt excepté dans le cadre de désastres naturels ou dans des circonstances indépendantes du contrôle d’un pays.
Cela exacerbe l’incertitude.
Lorsque les dirigeants européens apportent leur aide, les opinions publiques et les marchés ont tendance à remettre en question leur honnêteté.
Si les problèmes résultent du Traité de Lisbonne, alors il faut le modifier.
De plus, l’aide ne devrait pas être uniquement accordée que sous certaines conditions, mais devrait s’accompagner d’un contrôle temporaire du budget national par un comité d’« experts » nommés par l’Union Européenne.
The history shows that simple promises made by the beneficiary countries are not enough.
Of course, the countries subjected to such measures will express their indignation.
But no one forces them to accept this money.
Moral considerations?
Here is your solution.
Notice that this would be a much more effective disciplinary mechanism than the defunct Stability and Growth Pact.
We could also ask ourselves the following question: how would Californians react if their state temporarily handed over its budget to an expert specifically appointed by President Barack Obama's administration?
In fact, it would not bother them too much.
The expert would not be of Californian origin, but American.
The public opinion would understand that he would act in the interest of the Californian state as well as that of the country.
The fact that California sends representatives to Washington, from whom these orders would emanate, would reassure them.
Europeans do not do things like this because they first and foremost see themselves as Greeks and Germans.
They do not interfere in the "sovereignty prerogatives" of other member states.
Germany is especially reluctant given its history during the Second World War, especially in Greece.
If Europe really wants to achieve its monetary union, it will have to overcome its past.
This union implies not only stronger economic ties, but also closer political ties.
Those with a solid emergency aid mechanism will really have to account for it.
They will have to answer to a strong European Parliament.
The electorate of German Chancellor Angela Merkel hates this kind of rescue because they know well who will be responsible.
Germans oppose anything that resembles European political integration.
But Germany also has a share of responsibility in this crisis.
It wanted an incredibly independent central bank that was not obligated to account for its actions, but today this bank has adopted a monetary policy that is excessively expansionary, thus critically worsening the situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece, and Spain).
Germany's huge current account surpluses have further worsened their situation.
In addition, its fiscal stimulus measures have not been sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has consequently benefited from the creation of the euro.
She should reciprocate.
She should encourage the creation of an emergency loan facility, as well as the political integration needed to make it possible.
She needs to provide more budgetary support.
Isn't she best positioned to push for a more responsible European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan horse that leads Europe toward a more mature political integration.
We can only hope.
